      "\n          MordellWeilGroup.mk_point E xâ‚ƒ yâ‚ƒ sorry\n```\n\nThen when we match `some s`, we know that `MordellWeilGroup.slope E P Q = some s`, which in turn means that (because of the definition of `MordellWeilGroup.slope`):\n1. `xâ‚پ = xâ‚‚`\n2. `yâ‚پ + yâ‚‚ + ... â‰  0`\n3. `s = (3*xâ‚پآ² + ...)/(...)`\n\nBut Lean may not store these facts in the proof state because it is done via pattern matching. \n\nHowever, in Lean, we can still use the definition of `MordellWeilGroup.slope` to deduce that if we get `some s`, then we are in that case (but we cannot directly access the definition of `slope` in the proof).\n\nBut in reality, we are working in the branch where `P.point = some (xâ‚پ, yâ‚پ)` and `Q.point = some (xâ‚‚, yâ‚‚)`, and `xâ‚پ = xâ‚‚` and `yâ‚پ + yâ‚‚ + ... â‰  0`, and then `MordellWeilGroup.slope E P Q = some ((3*xâ‚پآ² + ...)/(...))`, so `s` is actually `(3*xâ‚پآ² + ...)/(...)`.\n\nBut in the `proof_goal`, we do not have these hypotheses. \n\nBut in Lean, perhaps the variables `xâ‚پ`, `yâ‚پ`, etc. are not actually arbitrary but are the coordinates from `P` and `Q`.\n\nTherefore, we probably have additional assumptions like `yâ‚پآ² + aâ‚پxâ‚پyâ‚پ + aâ‚ƒyâ‚پ = xâ‚پآ³ + aâ‚‚xâ‚پآ² + aâ‚„xâ‚پ + aâ‚†`, etc.\n\nBut in the `proof_goal`, these do not appear.\n\nBut perhaps the problem is not intended to include those assumptions because it is only asking for an algebraic identity that holds regardless of whether `(xâ‚پ, yâ‚پ)` is on the curve (but that cannot be the case, because we are trying to",
